To obtain the current value of `net.ipv4.tcp_rmem` in C, you can read the contents of `/proc/sys/net/ipv4/tcp_rmem`. Here's an example of how you might do that:

```c
#include <stdio.h>
#include <stdlib.h>
#include <string.h>

int main() {
    FILE *fp;
    int min, default_size, max;
    char buffer[1024];

    // Open the tcp_rmem proc file
    fp = fopen("/proc/sys/net/ipv4/tcp_rmem", "r");
    if (fp == NULL) {
        perror("Failed to open /proc/sys/net/ipv4/tcp_rmem");
        return -1;
    }

    // Read the contents of the file into a buffer
    if (fgets(buffer, sizeof(buffer), fp) == NULL) {
        perror("Failed to read from /proc/sys/net/ipv4/tcp_rmem");
        fclose(fp);
        return -1;
    }
    fclose(fp);

    // Parse the buffer to extract min, default, and max values
    if (sscanf(buffer, "%d %d %d", &min, &default_size, &max) != 3) {
        fprintf(stderr, "Failed to parse tcp_rmem values\n");
        return -1;
    }

    // Output the values
    printf("tcp_rmem min:%d default:%d max:%d\n", min, default_size, max);

    return 0;
}
```

This code opens the file located at `/proc/sys/net/ipv4/tcp_rmem` for reading and then reads a line from it into a buffer. The `sscanf` function is used to parse the three integer values from the buffer, which correspond to the minimum, default, and maximum values of the TCP receive buffer size.

Compile and run this program to print the current `net.ipv4.tcp_rmem` settings in your environment. Remember that this program should be run with sufficient permissions to read the file, typically as the root user, or make sure normal users have the appropriate read permissions for that file.

OpenBSD uses a different set of TCP tuning parameters compared to Linux, and the direct equivalent of `net.ipv4.tcp_rmem` as found in Linux is not present in OpenBSD. Instead, OpenBSD provides other mechanisms for configuring network-related parameters, and it focuses more on sensible defaults with less manual tweaking compared to Linux.

For setting TCP buffer sizes on OpenBSD, you can use the following sysctl variables:

- `net.inet.tcp.recvspace`: The default receive buffer size for TCP sockets.
- `net.inet.tcp.sendspace`: The default send buffer size for TCP sockets.

These parameters define the default buffer sizes for TCP sockets upon their creation, and they may impact the maximum buffer sizes as well. However, OpenBSD's TCP stack will automatically tune and manage buffer sizes to a certain extent.

To read the current values of these variables within a C program on OpenBSD, you would use the `sysctl` family of functions. Here's a simple example:

```c
#include <stdio.h>
#include <sys/types.h>
#include <sys/sysctl.h>

int main() {
    int recvspace, sendspace;
    size_t len = sizeof(recvspace);

    // Get the default TCP receive buffer size
    if (sysctlbyname("net.inet.tcp.recvspace", &recvspace, &len, NULL, 0) == -1) {
        perror("sysctlbyname(net.inet.tcp.recvspace) failed");
        return 1;
    }

    len = sizeof(sendspace);
    // Get the default TCP send buffer size
    if (sysctlbyname("net.inet.tcp.sendspace", &sendspace, &len, NULL, 0) == -1) {
        perror("sysctlbyname(net.inet.tcp.sendspace) failed");
        return 1;
    }

    printf("TCP receive buffer size: %d\n", recvspace);
    printf("TCP send buffer size: %d\n", sendspace);

    return 0;
}
```

This code retrieves the TCP receive and send buffer sizes using the `sysctlbyname` function. Ensure your C program includes the proper headers for these sysctl functions on OpenBSD.

