As of my knowledge cutoff date in early 2023, OpenBSD does not provide direct sysctl parameters that specifically set the maximum TCP socket buffer sizes in the same way that Linux does with `net.ipv4.tcp_rmem` and `net.ipv4.tcp_wmem`. OpenBSD has a different philosophy, favoring simplicity and smart defaults with minimal need for manual tuning.

However, OpenBSD does have sysctl settings that can influence the overall network stack behavior, including memory usage for buffers. These settings may affect the maximum buffer sizes indirectly:

- `kern.sbmax`: This parameter defines the maximum size of all mbuf clusters used for socket buffers within the system. It sets an upper limit on how much memory can be consumed by socket buffers but it is not specifically for TCP sockets or per-connection buffer size.

Here is an example of how you might query this value in C on an OpenBSD system:

```c
#include <stdio.h>
#include <sys/types.h>
#include <sys/sysctl.h>

int main() {
    int sbmax;
    size_t len = sizeof(sbmax);

    // Get the maximum size of socket buffers
    if (sysctlbyname("kern.sbmax", &sbmax, &len, NULL, 0) == -1) {
        perror("sysctlbyname(kern.sbmax) failed");
        return 1;
    }

    printf("Maximum socket buffer size: %d\n", sbmax);

    return 0;
}
```

Remember, these internal settings are tuned by OpenBSD developers to work well under various conditions without user intervention. Also, there is the `SO_RCVBUF` and `SO_SNDBUF` socket options which can be set using `setsockopt()` to control the receive and send buffer sizes on a per-socket basis, and they may be subject to `kern.sbmax` limitations.

Always refer to the most recent OpenBSD documentation and the `sysctl` man page (`man sysctl`) for the appropriate guidance on system parameters. The manual is a definitive source to verify which sysctl settings are available on your specific version of OpenBSD and how they behave.

NetBSD, like OpenBSD, does not exactly mirror the Linux `tcp_rmem` and `tcp_wmem` parameters. However, NetBSD is more similar to Linux in that it provides more tunable parameters for the TCP/IP stack through the `sysctl` interface.

In NetBSD, the following `sysctl` variables can be used to control the buffer sizes for TCP networking:

- `net.inet.tcp.recvspace`: This `sysctl` variable sets the default receive buffer size for TCP sockets.
- `net.inet.tcp.sendspace`: This `sysctl` variable sets the default send buffer size for TCP sockets.
- `net.inet.tcp.recvbuf_max`: This `sysctl` variable determines the maximum receive window size for a TCP connection. It is the closest equivalent to the third value of `net.ipv4.tcp_rmem` in Linux.
- `net.inet.tcp.sendbuf_max`: This `sysctl` variable determines the maximum send buffer size for TCP connections.

The `recvbuf_max` and `sendbuf_max` parameters essentially set hard limits on the receive and send buffer sizes that auto-tuning mechanisms would not exceed. These parameters can be viewed or set using the `sysctl` command-line utility or programmatically via the `sysctl` system call in C.

To retrieve the `net.inet.tcp.recvbuf_max` value in C on NetBSD, you could do something like the following:

```c
#include <stdio.h>
#include <sys/param.h>
#include <sys/sysctl.h>

int main() {
    int mib[4];
    size_t len;
    int recvbuf_max;

    len = sizeof(recvbuf_max);

    mib[0] = CTL_NET;
    mib[1] = AF_INET;
    mib[2] = IPPROTO_TCP;
    mib[3] = TCPCTL_RECVBUF_MAX;  // This may differ based on NetBSD version

    if (sysctl(mib, 4, &recvbuf_max, &len, NULL, 0) == -1) {
        perror("sysctl() failed");
        return 1;
    }

    printf("Max TCP receive buffer size: %d\n", recvbuf_max);

    return 0;
}
```

This example constructs the necessary Management Information Base (MIB) array that `sysctl` requires to locate the correct system variable. The MIB is effectively a path through the sysctl hierarchy to the desired variable (`net.inet.tcp.recvbuf_max` in this case).

Please note that the exact MIB for `TCPCTL_RECVBUF_MAX` may vary between different NetBSD versions, and you should verify the macro definition in the appropriate header file or through the NetBSD documentation. The code snippet is intended as a starting point and might need adjustments to work on specific versions of NetBSD. Always refer to the official NetBSD documentation for accurate and updated information.

Yes, FreeBSD has parameters similar to those of Linux for tuning TCP socket buffer sizes, including maximum buffer sizes. FreeBSD uses the `sysctl` interface for tuning many aspects of the kernel, including the network stack.

For TCP buffer size settings on FreeBSD, the following `sysctl` variables are commonly used:

- `net.inet.tcp.recvspace`: The default receive buffer size for TCP sockets.
- `net.inet.tcp.sendspace`: The default send buffer size for TCP sockets.
- `kern.ipc.maxsockbuf`: The maximum allowed size for a socket buffer (both send and receive). This is the setting that is most similar to the maximum buffer size (the third value) set by `net.ipv4.tcp_rmem` and `net.ipv4.tcp_wmem` in Linux.

You can query or set these values using the `sysctl` command, and similarly, you can programmatically access or modify these values using the `sysctl` system call in a C program.

Here's an example of how you would retrieve the `kern.ipc.maxsockbuf` value in C on FreeBSD:

```c
#include <stdio.h>
#include <sys/types.h>
#include <sys/sysctl.h>

int main() {
    int maxsockbuf;
    size_t len = sizeof(maxsockbuf);

    // Get the maximum socket buffer size
    if (sysctlbyname("kern.ipc.maxsockbuf", &maxsockbuf, &len, NULL, 0) == -1) {
        perror("sysctlbyname(kern.ipc.maxsockbuf) failed");
        return 1;
    }

    printf("Max socket buffer size: %d\n", maxsockbuf);

    return 0;
}
```

This code retrieves the maximum allowed socket buffer size using `sysctlbyname`, which is a convenient wrapper for the `sysctl` call that allows you to specify the MIB via a string representation. This max buffer size would apply to TCP connections as well as other socket types.

When tuning these parameters, it is important to understand the effects on the system and test any changes under typical workloads. Excessive buffer sizes can lead to wasted memory and potentially decrease system performance.

Refer to the FreeBSD handbook and the relevant man pages (using commands like `man sysctl` and `man tcp`) for further details about these kernel parameters and how to properly apply such configurations.

